2. The measure `WignerMeasure μ ν n` on `WignerSpace n` is the product measure where for each `p : Index n`, the coordinate `ω p` is independent and has measure `wignerMeasureDist μ ν n p`. 
   - If `p = (i, j)` with `i = j`, then `wignerMeasureDist μ ν n p = ν`.
   - Otherwise, `wignerMeasureDist μ ν n p = μ`.
3. The diagonal entry `(i, i)` of the Wigner Matrix is constructed from `ω (⟨(i, i), le_refl i⟩)`, because for `ω : WignerSpace n`, we have `wignerMatrixEntryFunction ω i i = ω (⟨(i, i), le_refl i⟩)` (by the first case of the definition of `wignerMatrixEntryFunction`).
3. The map `ω ↦ (wignerMatrixMap n ω) i i` is the same as `ω ↦ ω (⟨(i, i), le_refl i⟩)` because of the definition of `wignerMatrixEntryFunction` and the fact that `wignerMatrixMap n ω = Matrix.of (wignerMatrixEntryFunction ω)`.

**Approach:**

1. The law of `(wignerMatrixMap n ω) i i` under `WignerMeasure μ ν n` is the same as the law of `ω (⟨(i, i), le_refl i⟩)` under `WignerMeasure μ ν n`.
2. By definition of `WignerMeasure μ ν n` as a product measure, the coordinates are independent and `ω (⟨(i, i), le_refl i⟩)` has law `ν`.

